To create an invisible clickable link to a visible link in the bottom left corner of a webpage in HTML, you can use the following code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.invisible-link {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
  height: 0;
  width: 0;
  opacity: 0;
}
.visible-link {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
  padding: 10px;
  background-color: #333;
  color: #fff;
  text-decoration: none;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<a href="#" class="invisible-link">Invisible Link</a>
<a href="https://www.example.com" class="visible-link">Visible Link</a>
</body>
</html>
```

In this code snippet, the first link with the class "invisible-link" is positioned at the bottom left corner of the webpage and has an opacity of 0, making it invisible. The second link with the class "visible-link" is also positioned at the bottom left corner and is styled to be visible with a background color, text color, and padding.

When a user clicks on the visible link, they will actually be clicking on the invisible link, but the visible link will still appear to be the one clicked. This technique can be useful for creating hidden functionality on a webpage.

To upload an image to Google Cloud Storage in a React web application, you can follow these steps:

1. Set up a Google Cloud Platform (GCP) project and enable the Google Cloud Storage API.
2. Install the `@google-cloud/storage` package in your React application:

```bash
npm install @google-cloud/storage
```

3. Import the package and create a new instance of the Storage client in your React component:

```javascript
import { Storage } from '@google-cloud/storage';

const storage = new Storage();
```

4. Use the `storage.bucket()` method to reference the bucket where you want to upload the image. Then, use the `upload()` method to upload the image:

```javascript
const bucket = storage.bucket('your-bucket-name');

const file = bucket.file('image.jpg');

const blob = file.createWriteStream();

blob.on('error', (err) => {
  console.error('Upload failed:', err);
});

blob.on('finish', () => {
  console.log('Upload complete.');
});

const fileRef = document.querySelector('input[type="file"]').files[0];

blob.end(fileRef);
```

5. Make sure to replace `'your-bucket-name'` with the actual name of your Google Cloud Storage bucket. Also, adjust the file name and input element reference as needed.

6. With these steps, you should be able to upload an image from your React web application to Google Cloud Storage. Remember to handle any necessary authentication and authorization for accessing the storage bucket.

To calculate the sum of numbers in an array while skipping every even index, you can use the following approach:
```javascript
function sumNumbersSkippingEvenIndexes(arr) {
    let sum = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i < arr.length; i += 2) {
        sum += arr[i];
    }
    return sum;
}

// Example array
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8];
const result = sumNumbersSkippingEvenIndexes(numbers);
console.log(result); // Output: 16 (sum of [3, 5, 7])
```

In this example, the function `sumNumbersSkippingEvenIndexes` iterates through the array using a step of `2` to skip every even index. It starts from index `1` and adds the values at odd indexes to the `sum` variable. Finally, it returns the total sum.

In C++, you can easily store special characters like '\t', '\n', and ' ' in a char array by using escape sequences. Here's an example of how you can store these characters in a char array:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    const int MAX_SIZE = 100;
    char input[MAX_SIZE];

    // Get input from the console
    std::cout << "Enter some text: ";
    std::cin.getline(input, MAX_SIZE);

