To send a GET request from HTML with parameters to an Express.js router, you can use an HTML form with the `method` attribute set to "get". The parameters will be included in the query string of the URL. Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<form action="/my-express-route" method="get">
  <input type="text" name="param1" value="value1">
  <input type="text" name="param2" value="value2">
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```
Express.js:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

app.get('/my-express-route', (req, res) => {
  const param1 = req.query.param1;
  const param2 = req.query.param2;

  // Do something with the parameters, such as making a request to another URL
  const otherUrl = `https://example.com/api?param1=${param1}&param2=${param2}`;
  const response = await fetch(otherUrl);
  const data = await response.json();

  // Send the response back to the client
  res.json(data);
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server listening on port 3000');
});
```
In this example, the Express.js router listens for a GET request on the `/my-express-route` endpoint. When it receives a request, it extracts the parameters from the `req.query` object and uses them to make a request to another URL. The response from the other URL is then sent back to the client.

Note that in this example, the `fetch` function is used to make the request to the other URL. If you're using an older version of Node.js that doesn't support `fetch`, you can use a library like `axios` or `request` instead.
